Recently, cyber attacks on the business world have become more frequent.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target has cost them hundreds of millions and, in some cases, billions of dollars.
Too many such attacks are not needed to damage the global economy.
The public sector is also not immune to such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data leak at the U.S. Office of Personnel Management.
Access to security and fingerprint data for 22 million employees was compromised.
There are known attempts by government-sponsored hackers to influence election results in a number of countries using stolen data.
Two recent cases of large amounts of data disclosure concern the Bundestag, Germany's federal parliament, and the theft of US Democratic National Committee emails.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology advances, data protection systems are becoming increasingly vulnerable.
There is also concern about a new kind of computer technology - computing on quantum computers, which use the microscopic properties of nature to vastly increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it will be able to crack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for an imminent digital apocalypse?
I would say, "It's not the time yet."
uantum computers are still in development, and it will take many years before they can be put into practice.
More importantly, major breakthroughs are taking place in the area of encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of using the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
Right.
Now we are preparing to fight quantum with the help of quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a short tour of the world of encryption.
To do this, we will need a briefcase, some important documents we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special code lock: when it is closed, it converts all text in documents into random numbers.
You put the documents in the briefcase, close the lock - at this very moment all the documents are converted to random numbers - and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on its way, you call James to provide the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila - you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important elements of coding.
Code - we call it the "encryption key."
It is like a password.
Call James to tell him the lock combination code.
This is called a "key exchange" -
guarantee that you securely get the encryption key from the right place.
And a lock that encodes and decodes a document.
This is called a "coding algorithm."
Using a key, it converts text in documents into random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that without a key, a document is very difficult to decrypt.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a portfolio and hacks it without the help of an encryption key and encoding algorithm, they will still not be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure key exchange method to transfer the encryption key to the right place.
However, the rapid development of computing power threatens a number of modern methods of key exchange.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to hack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was hacked.
As computers became more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today, we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outwit each other.
And when quantum computers appear in the next 10-15 years, they will be able to hack even faster the complex mathematics that underlies many modern encryption systems.
The quantum computer is likely to turn our current reliable fortress into a simple house of cards.
We have to find a way to defend our fortress.
In recent years, there has been an increasing amount of research into the use of quantum effects to enhance cryptosecurity.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high-quality keys, secure key exchange, and a sophisticated algorithm?
Advances in science and technology threaten two of these three elements.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But to date, they are not entirely random.
Today, we create encryption keys from sequences of random numbers generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In the numbers generated by the program or mathematical formula, somehow there is a certain pattern.
The less random numbers are - in scientific terms: the less entropy they contain - the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos have fallen victim to an inventive attack.
The output combinations of the slot machines were recorded for some time before being analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the reels.
That, in turn, made it possible to predict the spins of the reels with high accuracy and get a big win.
Encryption keys can also be exposed to similar risks.
A truly random number generator is needed for secure encryption.
For many years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts to date are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
So it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an infinite stream of random numbers at high speed,
which will thwart all of these potential criminals at the casino.
A number of top universities and companies around the world are engaged in creating truly random number generators.
The first quantum generator created at my company was one by two meters in size and was placed on an optical table.
Later we were able to reduce it to the size of the server box.
Today it is the size of a PCI card connected to a standard computer.
It is the fastest truly random number generator in the world.
Its output is a billion random numbers per second.
Today, cloud providers, banks, and government agencies around the world are using it to strengthen security.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unresolved: the threat to the secure exchange of keys.
Modern methods of key exchange are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or D, which is based on the fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
The quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Let me give you an example of how this works.
Let's go back to exchanging codes for the castle with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with a code message, we will use quantum effects on the laser to create a code and send it to James over a regular optical fiber.
We believe that Dr. No will try to hack access to the data exchange.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch quantum keys along the way will leave fingerprints that James and you can detect.
This will eliminate the intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Because such security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer, or even any supercomputer of the future, will not be able to hack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities as well as the defence sector to develop this promising technology into next-generation security tools.
The Internet of Things heralds an era in which 25-30 billion devices are expected to interact by 2020.
Trust in the systems that support these devices is vital to the proper functioning of our society in the world of the Internet of Things.
I bet that quantum technology can provide that trust, allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thank you.
