My job is to help computers communicate about the world around them.
There are many ways to do this, but I like to help computers talk about what they see and understand.
For example, in this picture, a modern computer vision algorithm can recognize that this is a woman and this is a dog.
He can say the woman is smiling.
He is even able to say that the dog is unusually sweet.
I work on this by thinking about how people understand and process data about the world.
What thoughts, memories and stories such a picture can awaken in people.
Everything that is connected with such situations.
You may have seen a similar dog before or spent time running along the beach as well, and this in turn evokes thoughts and memories of a past vacation, of time spent on the beach, or of a time when you were running somewhere with other dogs.
One of my main principles is to help computers understand what it means to have this kind of experience, to understand what we share, what we believe and what we feel, because then we will be ready to start involving computer technology in processes that complement our own experience.
To dig deeper, a few years ago I started helping computers write stories based on a series of images.
And one day, while working, I asked the computer what he thought about going to Australia.
He looked at the pictures and saw the koala.
He did not know what a koala was, but said he considered it a curious creature.
Then I shared with him a series of images about burning houses.
He looked at the pictures and said: "Amazing view Awesome"
Goosebumps ran down my back.
He looked at the horrible, life-destroying event and thought it was something positive.
I realized that he recognized the contrasts, the shades of red and yellow, and thought it deserved a positive assessment.
In part he did it because most of the images I gave him were positive.
Because people tend to share positive images when they talk about their experiences.
When was the last time you saw a selfie at a funeral?
I realized that by perfecting artificial intelligence, task by task, data by array, I had created huge gaps, holes and gaps in what he could understand.
And in doing so, I have encoded every possible kind of prejudice.
Gaps that reflect human biases encoded in the data, such as bias and stereotypes.
I thought about the evolution of technology that led me to where I was then - how the first color photos were calibrated by the skin of white women, which meant the color photos were not adapted to dark faces.
And the same prejudice, the same gap, was observed in the 1990s.
And the same information gap we still have today is how well we can recognize a variety of human faces using facial recognition technology.
I was thinking about the latest research, where we tend to limit our thinking to one set of data and one problem.
And by doing so, we were creating more gaps and biases that AI could develop even more.
I realized that we needed to think more about how the technologies we are working with today will look like in 5 and 10 years.
Humanity is evolving slowly, over time correcting problems in the interaction between humans and the environment.
Artificial intelligence, by contrast, is evolving at an incredible rate.
And that means it's really important to think carefully about it right now - to reflect on our own gaps, our own prejudices, and how it affects the technologies we create, and to discuss what modern technologies will mean in the future.
Top managers and scientists around the world are talking about what they think artificial intelligence will be like in the future.
Stephen Hawking warns: "AI can end humanity."
Elon Musk warns that this is one of the greatest existential risks our civilization has ever faced.
Bill Gates is perplexed: "I don't understand why people are not concerned."
But these opinions are only part of the story.
Mathematics, models, and the fundamental building blocks of artificial intelligence are what we call access and what we work with.
We have open source tools for machine learning and intelligence that we are willing to share.
And beyond that, we can share our experiences.
Share your knowledge about technology and how we are concerned about it and how we are concerned about it.
We can discuss what we love.
We can anticipate which aspects of technology may become the most useful and which the most problematic over time.
If we all focus on an open dialogue about AI for the future, it will help create an atmosphere of shared awareness of what AI is now, what it can become, and what we need to do to get the most appropriate outcome for us.
We already see and know all this about the technologies used today.
We use smartphones, digital assistants and robot vacuum cleaners.
Are they evil?
Maybe sometimes.
Are they useful?
Absolutely.
And they are all different.
And in them you already see a beam of light illuminating our future.
The future begins with what we are creating and building right now.
We are launching a domino effect that will determine the path of AI development.
Right now, we are shaping the AI of the future.
Technologies that immerse us in augmented realities are bringing past worlds back to life.
Technologies that help people share experiences when they have difficulty communicating.
Technologies based on understanding streaming visual worlds are being used for unmanned vehicles.
Technologies based on image understanding and language generation are evolving into technologies that help visually impaired people better access the visual world.
But we also see how technology can lead to problems.
Today, we have technologies that analyze our innate physical characteristics - such as skin color or facial features - to determine whether we can be criminals or terrorists.
We have technology that analyzes data about us, even data such as gender or race, to determine whether we can get a loan.
All we see now is just one shot from the evolution of artificial intelligence.
Because where we are now is just a moment in this evolution.
This means that everything we do today will have an impact on our future.
If we want AI to evolve to help people, we need to define the goals and strategies that will set that path now.
I would like to see something that fits well with people, blends with our culture and environment.
Technologies that help those of us who suffer from neurological or other diseases to make life equally difficult for everyone.
Technologies that work regardless of your skin color or demographic characteristics.
Today, I am focused on the technologies that will be with us tomorrow and in 10 years.
AI can become anything.
But in this case, it is not a self-driving machine with no final destination.
We control this machine.
We choose when to accelerate and when to slow down.
We choose when we need to turn.
We choose what the AI of the future will be like.
There are countless things that artificial intelligence can become.
And it will become a lot of things.
And our task today is to find out exactly what we need to invest in AI so that the results obtained become the best for all of us.
Thank you
