Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, will reproduce and repair themselves.
So, I'm going to show you what I think is the current stage of industrial development, and then compare it to some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite sophisticated, new and amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us into space - 5 years, 2.5 million pieces.
But on the other hand, if we look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can be collected in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a DNA chain with three billion base pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So, natural systems, in all their complexity, are extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy efficient.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can regenerate themselves over a long life.
So there is something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think there are four key factors to consider.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and machines.
And we need to break them down into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of construction processes.
Then we need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to curl up or reconfigure.
We will need a certain amount of energy that will allow us to activate all of this, make the parts able to assemble according to the program.
And we need some kind of back-up error correction system to ensure the successful construction of what we want.
I'm going to show you some of the projects we're working on with our colleagues at MIT to achieve this self-assembling future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These are projects - large-scale reconfigurable robots - 2.5 and 3.5 meter proteins.
Mechanical electrical devices and sensors are built into them.
You paint what you need to curl up into a sequence of angles - minus 120, minus 120, 0, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of angles or turns, and you send that sequence over the cord.
Each block receives its own message - minus 120. It turns to this corner, checks if everything is correct and passes the information to the neighbor.
And these are the brilliant scientists, engineers, designers who worked on this project.
And I think it really raises the question: is there a possibility of a different scale here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, lots of man-hours to make this 2.5 meter robot.
Will we really be able to scale up? Will we really be able to integrate robotics into every part?
The next project addresses this issue, looks at the passive nature, or tries to get modification programmability passively.
But he goes one step further and tries to get a real calculation.
Basically, it has the most fundamental building block of computing, the logical element of a digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
This is the "AND-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron - the element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedrons for input.
One for user input, this is the way you put bricks.
Another is for information from previous laid bricks.
And then it displays information in three-dimensional space.
So, this means that the user can start moving the bricks in the right direction.
His calculations are based on what was done before and what you told him to do.
And now it starts to move in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left side, the 1,1 input equals 0 at the output, moving down.
On the right side, the 0,0 input is 1 at the exit, which means moving upwards.
And what really matters is that our structures now contain blueprints of what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So, it means that we have some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-directed reproduction, because the structures contain clear blueprints.
If errors appear, you can replace the part.
All local information is stored so you know how to correct it.
So you can have something that moves and reads information and can pass it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The latest project I'll show you is called Offset Chains, and this is perhaps the most exciting example of what we have now of passive self-assembling systems.
It combines reconfiguration and programming capabilities and creates a completely passive system.
Basically, we have a chain of elements.
All elements are completely identical and biased.
So every chain or every element wants to turn right or left.
And when you build a chain, you essentially program it.
You tell each block where it should turn: right or left.
So when you shake the chain, it folds into the configuration you have programmed - in this case, into a spiral, or in this case, two cubes next to each other.
So, in general, you can program any three-dimensional form - or one-dimensional, two-dimensional - from these absolutely passive circuits.
So what does this tell us about the future?
I think it tells us that there are new possibilities for self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, buildings, machines.
New programming is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new possibilities in computing.
We will have spatial computers.
Imagine that our buildings, bridges, cars, all our bricks could make calculations.
This is an amazing parallel and distributed computing power, new design possibilities.
This is an incredible potential.
I think the projects that I have shown you are only a small step towards the future, if we introduce these new technologies, towards a new self-assembling future.
Thank you.
