The fire in the Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul occurred on July 18.
More than 200 firefighters fought for several hours for a monument of Gothic architecture.
However, they were unable to save the stained glass windows of the Louis II era and the unique organ of the Baroque era.
The situation was brought under control only three hours after the start of the fire.
No one was injured in the incident.
The current fire is not the first in the history of the church.
In 1972, a fire destroyed its roof.
It took 13 years to clean up the consequences of that fire.
The cathedral was only reopened for parishioners in 1985.
