It is believed that only sighted people can drive a car.
Until recently, it was believed that safe and independent driving was an impossible task for a blind person.
Hello, I am Denis Hong, and we are giving the blind freedom and independence by developing cars for the visually impaired.
Before talking about this car for the blind, I will briefly talk about another project I have been working on, called DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start," and without his participation the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, finishing third in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NFB, tasked a research committee with developing a car that could be operated independently and safely by a blind person.
We decided to try our hand at it because we thought, "Hey, what's the hard part of it?
We already have an autonomous car.
Let's put a blind man in it - and the case is over, right? "
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NFS wanted not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that the blind could drive on their own.
So we had to scrap everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype of a buggy car to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind young people from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that the car was designed to operate in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a flat, enclosed car park, where even traffic lanes are restricted by red signal cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So, how does it work?
Well, it's a pretty complicated system, but let me explain, maybe even simplify it.
So, it has three components.
This is tactile perception, calculation and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver does not see anything, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
For this purpose, an initial parameter meter is used.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like the inner ear of a person.
This information is then transmitted to a GPS device to assess the location of the vehicle.
Two cameras are used to detect lanes on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the vehicle to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking vehicle, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the vehicle.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer performs two stages.
First of all, it is processing this information in order to get an idea of the space: identifying traffic lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then communicating this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to drive.
So, we can also give advice on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is how to get this information and instructions across to a blind person who does not have the quick and accurate response needed to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a range of interface technologies for the blind:
A three-dimensional ping sound system, a vibrating vest, a steering wheel with sound signals, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the leg.
But today we will only talk about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motorized finger joints, instructing the driver how to steer: direction and angle of turn.
Another device is SpeedStrip.
Initially, this is a massage chair.
The vibration is used to provide the driver with speed information as well as guidance on the use of gas and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, it is transmitted to devices via a computer.
DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very effective.
But the problem is that these are instructional prompting devices.
They don't actually give you the freedom to govern, don't they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left," "right," "speed up," "stop."
We call him "an annoying backseat passenger."
That's why we're moving away from teaching prompts and concentrating our attention on informative devices.
An excellent example of such an interface is AirPix.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air escapes, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring a palm to this panel and "see" traffic lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
The driver can also change the frequency at which the air is released and possibly the air temperature.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So here you see the left and right camera of the car and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we showcase a simulator, a blind person driving a car using AirPix.
This simulator has proven to be very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different types of special interfaces.
This is how the system works briefly.
After all, this is a prototype car for the blind, and it will not be released on the roadway until they are convinced of its absolute safety.
And I sincerely believe that it is quite possible.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will auto insurance rules change?
What are the conditions under which a driver's license will be issued?
Beyond the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls to overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the spin-off technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve vehicle safety for the sighted.
Or for the blind. Find their use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in the classroom writes on a blackboard, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
This is priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Many thanks.
(Applause)
